41529242.name: At the Quinte Hotel (full)
41529242.description:
Global Mechanic presents a fluid, vibrant and kinetic riff on one of Al Purdy's best-known poems, recalling the experimental, interpretive work of Norman McLaren. It's not a literal adaptation, but something more free-associative that visually accompanies the text while staying true to the playful, erudite spirit of the poem and Al Purdy's imagination. Almost all the animation was done in-camera, except for a bit of compositing after the fact.

For more info, including a making-of video visit: http://globalmechanic.com/video/At_the_Quinte_Hotel_Making

85498724.name: Vive la Rose
85498724.description:
Vive la Rose is a short film Bruce Alcock made for the NFB. It’s a rather tragic love story of a fisherman and his beloved, based on a traditional Newfoundland song performed by Emile Benoit.

To convey the history and character of this story of unrequited love, we rooted the film on location in Newfoundland, using a combination of live action and animation to tell the story. Bruce loves mixing up elements of things, so we combined digital and hand-made production – ink drawings with a variety of romantic and associative elements and objects – to create a stop motion film. Because it was all shot on location, we were able to make use of sunlight and the physical realities of the location. The film looks like it could have been made in the 1800’s: we used still cameras but the digital underpinning made it work.

85776550.name: SweaterLodge
85776550.description:
SweaterLodge was an incredible multi-media exhibit chosen to represent Canada at the Venice Biennale of Architecture, created by Pechet and Robb Art and Architecture. We collaborated with them to create an atmospheric visual feast of film and animation: a multi-projector video production powered by viewers pedalling stationary bikes linked to computers.

We spliced and animated film together in a moving, twirling collage of riffs on the life cycle of a city. The imagery was all about construction and destruction, recycling and consuming, with crazy stuff like giant bottles as skyscrapers, and ferns taking over the city. Viewers became part of the event. By pedalling the bikes slow, fast or backwards, they became DJs of sorts: scratching and mixing video images and sound, in and out of sync with one another, all playing their own riotous melody that worked perfectly with the curious and quirky quality of SweaterLodge.

85780167.name: I Send You This Cadmium Red
85780167.description: Unprecedented and engaging, I Send You This Cadmium Red is at once a feast for and exploration of the senses. Based on the correspondence between artist John Christie and Booker prize winning author John Berger, and scored by the music of Gavin Bryars.  Bruce Alcock's stunning projections merge to kaleidoscopic effect against the live performance from the actors and musicians making this a film, a painting, an essay, a concert - and yes, a play - all at once. Therefore none of the above. It's something else entirely. It's extraordinary.

86731887.name: Just Clicks
86731887.description:
At Global Mechanic, we get asked a lot about what we do. Generally, they’re the ‘what’s behind the curtain’ kind of questions, since our process can seem mysterious when you’re on the outside looking in. We work in many mediums, and love mixing art and technology to create unique work – beautiful things that often defy the conventional boundaries of descriptors like ‘digital’ and ‘campaigns.’ But how do we explain our process when we end up in a different place every time? And how do we show people how we work for so many different industries, on so many different kinds of problems?

So, we ventured to try and explain the hothouse that is Global Mechanic. What makes us tick. What makes us different. How we help our clients – and their customers – see the world in a new way. We wanted to show AND tell our story, while having some fun along the way, because, well, that’s exactly how we work!
